From: CDE packaging <packaging@cdesktopenv>
Subject: Dt: disable Motif color object globally for CDE clients

Modern Motif (2.3.x as shipped by Fedora) calls XConvertSelection on
_MOTIF_DEFAULT_COLORS from inside the Initialize method of widgets that
pull in the XmDisplay color object. The desktop color server (dtsession)
owns that selection.

Inside dtsession itself the request deadlocks: the call happens before the
main event loop starts, and dtsession cannot reply to its own selection
request. In every other CDE client the request only incurs a libXt
selection timeout per widget (default ~5s), but front-panel-heavy clients
(dtwm, dtfile, dtmail, dtcm) initialise dozens of widgets, so logins
become unbearably slow even when they eventually succeed.

Setting *useColorObj:False in the Dt common app-defaults (every CDE Motif
client does `# include "Dt"`) skips the color object lookup entirely.
This is safe because dtsession's color server already writes the palette
foreground/background to the X resource database via _DtAddToResource;
Motif still reads correct colors.

--- a/lib/DtSvc/DtUtil2/Dt.ad
+++ b/lib/DtSvc/DtUtil2/Dt.ad
@@ -17,6 +17,20 @@

 *foregroundThreshold:	70

+!#
+!# Disable Motif's per-process color object. Modern Motif (2.3.x as
+!# shipped by Fedora) calls XConvertSelection on _MOTIF_DEFAULT_COLORS
+!# from inside widget Initialize. The selection owner is dtsession;
+!# inside dtsession itself the request deadlocks (the event loop has
+!# not started yet), and in every other CDE client it incurs a 5-second
+!# libXt selection timeout per widget, which the front-panel-heavy
+!# clients (dtwm, dtfile, dtmail) make excruciatingly visible.
+!#
+!# CDE writes its palette colors into the X resource database
+!# (DtAddToResource), so disabling the color object lookup is safe:
+!# Motif still gets the correct foreground/background from xrdb.
+!#
+*useColorObj:		False
+
